    <h1>
        Homework #2 - ASP.NET MVC with Ajax</h1>
    <p>
        <a href="http://www.tampadev.org/newsletters/TampaDevJun2009.pdf" target="_blank"><img src="../../Content/TampaDevJun2009.png" style="border:0" alt="April 2009 Newsletter" align="right" /></a>The 
        third meeting,
        <a href="http://www.tampadev.org/Meetings/Details/IntroductionjQueryASPNETMVC"
            target="_blank">Introduction to jQuery with ASP.NET MVC</a>, at
        the <a href="http://www.tampadev.org/" target="_blank">Tampa ASP.NET MVC Developer Group</a> 
        focused on building UI&#39;s for ASP.NET MVC Web Applications.
        <a href="http://www.davidhayden.com/" target="_blank">David Hayden</a> presented material on the ASP.NET Ajax Helpers in the ASP.NET MVC 
        Framework as well as examples on MvcContrib and ASP.NET MVC Futures. David put 
        together a screencast on the use of ASP.NET MVC Ajax Helpers per his 
        presentation:
        <a href="http://www.tampadev.org/News/Details/MvcAjaxHelpersScreencast" target="_blank">ASP.NET 
        MVC Ajax Helpers - Ajax.ActionLink and Ajax.BeginForm - Screencast</a></p>
    <p>
        Your homework assignment is to use the ASP.NET MVC Ajax Helpers to &quot;ajaxify&quot; the 
        creation, editing, viewing, and deletion of Customers in this ASP.NET MVC Web 
        Application similar to how David presented at the last meeting and showed in the 
        screencast. It does not have to be exactly like presented at the meeting. Use 
        the Ajax Helpers how you think they should be used to provide a richer user 
        experience for the end user.</p>
    <p>If you would rather use jQuery instead of the Ajax Helpers, go for it!</p>
